text: When I talked about the acceleration, I think open source is one of the key aspects of that acceleration. So like you were talking about, there are multiple of these items that we use out there that have a thousand people working on a code base in the cloud that are making it so the tools, think about the barrier to entry to try some of these things, has gone dramatically down. So when I showed up first working for Jim full time, I did the internship, gave me the offer, and I showed up in 2005. And the very first thing he said was, I hear all about neural networks, build me one. Tell me if these things have any practice. And I was like, okay. So I started reading all the literature. I went up to like the Columbia AI department, their computer science department. I was asking them. I went into the code and I started building one. It took me three months to build a neural network, a back propagation network that was like three layers deep. And I ran it. It was awful. It was like it basically, they went all in on value and then into 1998. And then at the end of 1999, switched over to momentum. And then. Fell apart like four times after that in 2003, I crushed again on the second half of the year growth rally. Anyway, so, but that exercise of three months to build this algorithm and to put it together and to test it, to find out that it didn't work. A neural network now is maybe 10 lines of code. You take this open source package. You basically, the algorithm's all done. And theirs is probably sort of like the equivalent of me coding it with Yahoo and scraping Yahoo. Theirs is vetted by multiple PhDs on a computer science background building these things. And you have access to them. So that barrier to entry on these has gone down to the point where it's again, accelerated. Now you have to be careful with them because there's a lot of dependencies that are stacking up from people working in open source. So there are certain things you need to know, like how to freeze a Python environment, like to figure out all the versions for everything that's coming through. And how do you make sure that those are lined up? So what you're putting together, like somebody could update a, one of the underlying dependencies of scikit-learn or something like that. And that could have. You know, a lot of things are going to be in the same place. And that's going to affect downstream what happens. So you've got to understand productionizing code, the willingness to work with those. Can it have this tremendous impact where you're essentially leveraging the best in the industry for specifically and bringing them into your organization through this open source. Now you have to evaluate those tools. This is the harder part. I think now, which is it used to be the harder part was building the tools. Now the harder part is so many of these, which ones are you using? What's the right one to do? And then figuring out which ones you're going to spend your time. And figuring out to adopt the skill and just learn how they work. And just basically where are you spending people's time inside of these because of all the infinite number of tools that are out there.
